  "prompt": "How do I solve [math]\\displaystyle\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)[/math]?",
  "response": "To evaluate the limit\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left( \\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x \\right),\n\\]\n\nlet's proceed step by step.\n\n### Step 1: Simplify the Expression Inside the Cube Root\n\nFirst, factor out \\( x^3 \\) from the expression inside the cube root:\n\n\\[\nx^2 - x^3 = -x^3 + x^2 = -x^3\\left(1 - \\frac{1}{x}\\right).\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Apply the Cube Root\n\nNow, apply the cube root to both sides:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3 \\left(1 - \\frac{1}{x}\\right)} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3} \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}.\n\\]\n\nSimplify \\(\\sqrt[3]{-x^3}\\):\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{-x^3} = -x.\n\\]\n\nSo the expression becomes:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = -x \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}.\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Substitute Back into the Original Limit\n\nSubstitute the simplified cube root back into the original limit:\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left( -x \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} + x \\right) = \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left( x \\left[ -\\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} + 1 \\right] \\right).\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Expand the Cube Root Using a Binomial Approximation\n\nFor large \\( x \\), \\( \\frac{1}{x} \\) is small. We can use the binomial approximation for the cube root:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} \\approx 1 - \\frac{1}{3x}.\n\\]\n\nTherefore,\n\n\\[\n-\\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} + 1 \\approx -\\left(1 - \\frac{1}{3x}\\right) + 1 = \\frac{1}{3x}.\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Multiply by \\( x \\) and Take the Limit\n\nSubstitute the approximation back into the expression:\n\n\\[\nx \\left( \\frac{1}{3x} \\right) = \\frac{1}{3}.\n\\]\n\nAs \\( x \\to \\infty \\), the higher-order terms vanish, and we are left with:\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left( \\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x \\right) = \\frac{1}{3}.\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\dfrac{1}{3}}\n\\]",
